  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\n\r\nAfter fixing https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/71594, Azure cloud provider updates the network configurations per instance, so that the nodes would be rebooted when they are added to ALB. But this introduces a problem, that the latest model of each instance is different now from VMSS.\r\n\r\nRefer https://github.com/Azure/aks-engine/issues/1615#issuecomment-513158712:\r\n\r\n> Initially, everything looks ok, but if you go to the instances in the VMSS pool you will see that you have a warning icon in the \"last model\".\r\n> \r\n> The app is still available, but if you press \"update\" in the VMSS instances you will lose the connectivity between the LB and the VMSS Instances, and later the \"last model\" column is with all the instances in \"yes\".\r\n> After this, the App is not accessible anymore.\r\n\r\nSo, Azure LoadBalancer would lose backends when the nodes are upgraded to the latest model.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nAzure LoadBalancer should still work when instances are upgraded to the latest model.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n/sig azure\r\n/kind bug\r\n/milestone v1.16\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g: `cat /etc/os-release`):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Network plugin and version (if this is a network-related bug):\r\n- Others:\r\n",
